Meta-análise

Following the same logic from Santana (2018), we fitted a model for each biomarker (in total, 6 models). In each model, we used the following variables: Type of exposure (3 levels); NSAID (3 levels), Dose (2 levels), and Exposure (2 levels). The model’s intercept was probably renamed in Santana by Global effect. The intercept basically means that we are in a scenario with: Acute Type of exposure; Diclofenac (NSAID); High Dose; and Hydric Exposure.

As Santana (2018), we modeled the standardized mean difference. We present the summary output of each model (a different biomarker). Some of the measures printed out means:

  • \(I^{2}\): the total remained heterogeneity;
  • \(Q_{M}\): if the variables/moderators are statistically significant, together. i.e., if there is a difference between levels in a general sense.

Graph

the graph follows the same idea as Santana’s. There they split the biomarkers into several figures. Here I was able to put everything together. Another difference is that here we are also able to look at the p-values. The dots are the standardized mean difference estimated and the horizontal lines are the 95% confidence intervals.

Referências

The statistical analysis was performed with the R language and environment for statistical computing (R Core Team, 2021). Barplots and percentage computations were used to describe and summarize the qualitative variables. A meta-analysis (Viechtbauer, 2010) was performed for each biomarker to understand and summarize the findings of the articles, in terms of type of exposure; NSAID; dose; and exposure. The main R packages used in this analysis were: dplyr (Wickham et al., 2021), tidyr (Wickham, 2021), stringr (Wickham, 2019), ggplot2 (Wickham, 2016), purrr (Henry and Wickham, 2020), and metafor (Viechtbauer, 2010).

R Core Team (2021). R: A language and environment for statistical computing. R Foundation for Statistical Computing, Vienna, Austria. URL https://www.R-project.org/

Wickham, H., François, R., Henry, L., Müller, K. (2021). dplyr: A Grammar of Data Manipulation. R package version 1.0.7. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=dplyr

Wickham, H. (2021). tidyr: Tidy Messy Data. R package version 1.1.3. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=tidyr

Wickham, H. (2019). stringr: Simple, Consistent Wrappers for Common String Operations. R package version 1.4.0. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=stringr

Henry, L., Wickham, H. (2020). purrr: Functional Programming Tools. R package version 0.3.4. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=purrr

Viechtbauer, W. (2010). Conducting meta-analyses in R with the metafor package. Journal of Statistical Software, 36(3), 1-48. https://doi.org/10.18637/jss.v036.i03
